{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582990"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.85,0.05,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47102"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1651"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"882"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47102"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to hospital in labour with strong regular contractions at 38 weeks gestation. She emigrated to Australia from Kenya three weeks ago and received little antenatal care throughout her pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She births her son vaginally three hours after presentation. On examination, the newborn appears well with a pulse rate of 140/min, respiratory rate 40/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Physical examination reveals the presence of a large anterior abdominal wall defect with viscera protruding through the base of the umbilical cord, covered by a thin membrane (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroschisis","Omphalocele","Umbilical hernia","Congenital diaphragmatic hernia","Meconium peritonitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defect pictured is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eomphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E. It is the result of failure of the midgut to return to the abdominal cavity during embryonic development, leading to herniation of abdominal viscera through the base of the umbilical cord. The protruding contents are covered by a thin, translucent membrane consisting of peritoneum and amnion. Omphalocele is associated with other congenital anomalies, particularly cardiac defects, chromosomal abnormalities such as trisomy 13 and 18, and Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by herniation of abdominal contents, usually small bowel and stomach, through a small paraumbilical defect to the right of the umbilical cord. There is no covering membrane and the umbilical cord is not involved. Gastroschisis is less commonly associated with other congenital anomalies compared to omphalocele.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E also presents as a midline abdominal mass, but is a smaller, reducible protrusion at the base of a normally inserted umbilical cord that is covered by skin. Most umbilical hernias close spontaneously by 12 months of age and rarely contain liver or bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital diaphragmatic hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when abdominal contents herniate through a defect in the diaphragm into the thoracic cavity. It presents with severe respiratory distress shortly after birth rather than an obvious abdominal wall defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeconium peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E results from antenatal bowel perforation and presents with abdominal distension, ascites and calcifications on abdominal x-ray. The abdominal wall is intact.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Omphalocele can be differentiated from gastroschisis by the involvement of the umbilical cord and presence of a membrane over viscera in omphalocele, whereas gastroschisis is characterised by free-floating bowel loops without any covering sac."],"references":["Piergiorgio Gamba, Paola Midrio. Abdominal wall defects: Prenatal diagnosis, newborn management and long-term outcomes, Sem Pediatr Surg. 2014;23(5):283-290. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25459013/","Christison-Lagay ER, Kelleher CM, Langer JC. Neonatal abdominal wall defects. Semin Fetal Neonatal Med. 2011;16(3):164-172. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21474399/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17359"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/